Character of Grinnell
Seen Through History
, By Susan Taylor
‘ "Something of the union~
. removing idealism of the
lenders_ of this college is a
spirit worth maintaining in our
me,” according to Prof. Alan
ones, history. Mr. Jones delivered the annual History of
ﬁrussell College lecture to the
new students and other inherited persons in Roberts Theaor Wednesday night. ’
Jones interpreted the story
at the college by studying the
character it processed under
ﬁle leadership of its various
installing treatments, rather
than relating happenings which
were significant in its physical
growth.
From the beginning, as the
holders and first trustees
ﬂedited, Grinnell was a center
of liberal ideas in learning, but
Elsa a Christian enterprise, the
'story teacher explained. He
pointed out, however, that the
goals or free inquiry and isolated study which were held
by the first trustees have not
enjoyed a consistent place
here, but rather were present
under~the leadership of some
treatments more than of others
Throughout the history of the
Mllege modifications of these
goals have taken place. But
om the beginning Jones explained, the college “was involved with the spirit of the
West, a dream of quest and of
opportunity.”
"A tradition of free inquiry
.was present from the beginning,” Jones said. “The origins
D! the college as a religious
land moral as well as an internet<
coal endeavor” were also explained
Looking back, Jones said,
one can observe the vision of
the trustees when they set up
their plan for an isolated place
[or study, away from the cards
of the world. However, he also
pointed out that as Grinnell
came more into the consciousness of the nations, its involve<
event in the affairs of men increased.
The college, though it gained
I national reputation in the
early part of the 20th century
 
still remained a small school
struggling for its ideals, he
said.
Mr. Jones cited many examples of the writing of members of the college community throughout its history to il—
lustrate the ideals which have
been continually held.
He pointed out that the con
sciousness of community increased with the building of the
residence calls,
”Compared to its past,"
Jones commented, “the college
is stronger than ever both intellectually and totally."
Alan Jones graduated from
Grinnell College in 1950 and returned as a member of the his
tony faculty in 1954. He has
been here since.
